<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-455-354  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 455 354.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computing Canada  July 6 1989 v15 n14 p39(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Erasable optical technology disk drives gaining momentum. (Featurereport)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rail, Michel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Erasable, or rewritable, optical disk drives make use ofmagneto-optical technology, in which writing and erasing isachieved by using laser light and magnetic field to alter the tapein a disk cartridge.andP;  The system is very stable.andP;  It is notsusceptible to magnetic field damage.andP;  The recording techniquedoes not require contact with the recording surface, so disk headcrashes are eliminated.andP;  The media does not lose integrity withrepeated use.andP;  The specific process of writing and reading involvea series of steps making use of laser heat and change of magneticpolarity.andP;  Erasable optical disks are suited to the sameapplications as traditional magnetic disks.andP;  They replace mostmagnetic tape applications.andP;  They are particularly suited to massstorage applications in CAD-CAM, medical imaging and publishing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Erasable Optical MemoryOptical DisksDisk DrivesMagneto-Optical Disk DrivesAnalysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>